"""
MKT Christ Commentary — John chapters 9–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-john-9-10.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-original/john.json (terminology carry-forward)
- data/echoes/john.json (OT connections already documented)
- scripts/zc-christ-john-1-2.py and zc-christ-john-3-4.py (terminology and register)

Key decisions in this range:
- "The Evangelist" consistently used (matching mkt-original and prior christ scripts)
- "Christ" for Messianic-identity discussions; "Jesus" for narrative-level references
- Directness levels stated in prose: "A direct…", "A type…", "A shadow…", "A revelation of God", "The theme of…", "A fulfillment"
- 9:5 ("I am the light of the world"): classified as direct — identical to 8:12; the sign that follows enacts the claim
- 9:6-7 (clay / Siloam): classified as type — Gen 2:7 new-creation allusion; "Sent" naming points to the mission of the Son
- 9:35-38 (Son of Man + worship): classified as direct — Dan 7:13-14 register; the cast-out man becomes the first confessor
- 9:39-41 (judgment by light): classified as fulfillment — Isa 6:9-10 / 29:18 reversal-of-blindness theme
- 10:11,14 ("I am the good shepherd"): classified as direct type fulfilling Ezek 34 (God as true shepherd) and Ps 23
- 10:16 (one flock, one shepherd): classified as fulfillment of Ezek 37:22-24 and Mic 5:4; Gentile mission anticipated
- 10:17-18 (lay down / take up): classified as revelation of God — voluntary atonement; authority over death is the Father's gift
- 10:30 ("I and the Father are one"): classified as direct Christological claim; the charge in v33 confirms the authorities heard it correctly
- 10:34-36 (Ps 82 defense): classified as direct — a fortiori argument for Christ's divine sonship
- 10:40-42 (retreat to Bethany; John's witness validated): classified as theme — the Baptist's preparatory word finally vindicated
- Chapter 9 treated as a unified enacted Christological disclosure: the Light of the World gives light
- Chapter 10 read as continuous with ch. 9 — addressed to the Pharisees who expelled the healed man (v1)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


JOHN = {
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: Christ\'s initiative is the governing fact of the encounter — he sees the man, not the reverse. The man born blind has not sought Jesus, cannot seek him, and has no knowledge of who approaches. The pattern anticipates the Shepherd\'s search of ch. 10 and the broader Johannine theme of election: it is not the sheep who find the shepherd but the shepherd who seeks his own. The blind man is found before he can believe.</p>',

    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: the disciples\' question — "who sinned, this man or his parents?" — imports the Deuteronomic retribution framework (Deut 28; cf. Job\'s friends) into an encounter where that framework will be dismantled. They assume the man\'s condition is a theological problem to be solved. Christ will reframe it as a Christological occasion. The disciples represent the limit of a theology that can only look backward to sin rather than forward to divine glory.</p>',

    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "so that the works of God might be displayed in him" overturns the entire theodicy. The man\'s blindness is not penal but purposive — a canvas on which divine action will be visible. The Evangelist does not explain why God permits suffering in general; he shows that in this case the end is the revelation of the Son of God. The theme of God\'s glory displayed through human limitation runs from Exodus (the hardening of Pharaoh to manifest God\'s power) into the Gospel\'s own theology of the cross (12:23–28).</p>',

    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "we must do the works of him who sent me while it is day; night is coming" — the urgency of Christ\'s mission is grounded in divine appointment, not human schedule. The language of sending (the Son sent by the Father) frames the healing that follows as a commissioned act. The "night" when no one can work anticipates the hour of darkness at the cross (13:30 — Judas goes out "and it was night"). Christ works because the Father sent him; the works are the Father\'s through the Son.</p>',

    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "While I am in the world, I am the light of the world" — the same claim Christ made in 8:12, now immediately before enacting it in sign. As in John 1:4–5 (life as light; light shining in darkness), the Prologue\'s cosmic claim is about to be concentrated in one man\'s opened eyes. The grammar is present tense and conditional on his presence in the world — pointing forward to the departure (16:28) after which the Paraclete will carry the light\'s work. The sign of ch. 9 is the exegesis of this claim.</p>',

    "6": '<p>A type: Christ forms clay with saliva and applies it to the man\'s eyes, recalling the creation of Adam from the dust of the ground (Gen 2:7, where God forms the man from the earth). The Evangelist presents Christ as performing a new-creation act — the one through whom all things were made (1:3) re-creates the eyes that nature formed incomplete. The use of clay connects the sign to the creation idiom: the Maker of eyes gives eyes. This is not magic technique; it is the Creator acting within his own creation.</p>',

    "7": '<p>A type: "Siloam," which the Evangelist translates as "Sent," is not incidental. The pool whose name means Sent is the place of cleansing for the man sent there by the one who is himself the Sent One — the Son sent by the Father (3:17; 5:36; 17:3). The healing is enacted through immersion in what bears the Christological name: to be washed in the "Sent" pool is, in the Evangelist\'s symbolic register, to encounter the mission of the Son. The man who was born blind receives sight precisely where the naming of the act matches the nature of the one who performs it.</p>',

    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: the neighbors\' recognition dispute — "is this the same man?" — introduces the Gospel\'s pattern of the Incarnation\'s disruptive presence. An ordinary person has been extraordinarily transformed; the community cannot reconcile who he was with who he now is. The inability to recognize transformation is one of the Evangelist\'s recurring themes: those who "see" in the ordinary sense cannot perceive what has happened in the spiritual register.</p>',

    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: the healed man\'s insistence — "I am the man" — uses the emphatic <em>egō eimi</em> construction that the Evangelist will repeatedly place in Christ\'s mouth as the divine self-declaration. Whether or not the echo is deliberate, the structural irony is present: the one who will come to say "I am the Son of Man" (v37) has just healed a man who says "I am he" — identity disclosed in the midst of communal confusion about who stands before them. The theme of unrecognized presence from 1:26 is operative.</p>',

    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: the question "how were your eyes opened?" is the Gospel\'s question in miniature. The whole of the Fourth Gospel is the answer to how human beings come to see — through encounter with Christ, through the Spirit given by him, through the word he speaks. The neighbors ask as curiosity; the Pharisees will ask as interrogation; Jesus will provide the ultimate answer in vv39–41. How does anyone see? Only through the one who is the light.</p>',

    "11": '<p>The theme of progressive Christological disclosure: the healed man\'s first identification of Christ is functional and ordinary — "the man they call Jesus." He knows only the name and what was done. The Evangelist narrates his understanding in ascending stages: "the man Jesus" (v11) → "a prophet" (v17) → the object of worship (v38). The pattern of growing recognition mirrors the Gospel\'s own strategy: readers who begin with "the man from Nazareth" are led to "My Lord and my God" (20:28).</p>',

    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: the healed man\'s honest ignorance — "I don\'t know" about where Jesus is — does not diminish his testimony about what Jesus did. The Evangelist consistently separates what is known (the sign, its effect) from what is not yet known (the full identity of the sign-worker). Faith grows from the known toward the unknown; the man who cannot say where Jesus is will, by the end of the chapter, worship the one who stands before him.</p>',

    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: the Pharisees are brought the sign they cannot deny and must adjudicate. The institutional structures of covenant discernment — the religious authorities trained to recognize God\'s action — are now confronted with the clearest possible evidence of that action. The Evangelist frames their examination as a trial in which the blind man is increasingly the defendant — and increasingly the model of faith — while the examiners are increasingly revealed as the ones who cannot see.</p>',

    "14": '<p>A shadow: the Sabbath timing is not incidental — the healing on the Sabbath activates the charge that will drive the institutional opposition to Christ through the remainder of the Gospel. Christ has been doing the works of the Father (v4) on the day of divine rest, which is precisely the claim he will make in 5:17 ("My Father is always at his work to this very day, and I too am working"). The shadow is this: the Sabbath was the sign of the Sinai covenant (Exod 31:13); Christ\'s Sabbath-healing signs the arrival of a new covenant reality — rest no longer confined to a day but given through the Son (Matt 11:28–29).</p>',

    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: the Pharisees\' repeated interrogation ("how did you receive your sight?") reveals that the fact of the healing is not in question — only its legitimacy. They are not investigating whether it happened but whether the one who did it is authorized. The Evangelist\'s irony: the authorities demand that the sign be accredited by their criteria, but the criteria are precisely what the sign is overturning. Christ is not seeking their authorization; he is the one through whom divine authorization is disclosed.</p>',

    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: the Pharisees\' division — "this man is not from God" (Sabbath breach) versus "how can a sinner perform such signs?" — is the Gospel\'s epistemological fault line. The first group reasons from precedent (law defines authorized action); the second reasons from evidence (the act itself attests the actor). The division will persist through ch. 10 (v19). The Evangelist positions the second question as the one the Gospel is answering: no one could perform these signs unless God were with him (3:2).</p>',

    "17": '<p>The theme of the prophet like Moses: the healed man\'s verdict — "He is a prophet" — names the category of Deut 18:15, the authoritative figure Israel was taught to expect who would speak with God\'s own authority. Christ is more than a prophet (1:17 — grace and truth came through Jesus Christ, not through Moses), but "prophet" is the honest first threshold of recognition. The Evangelist allows the man\'s faith to name what it can name at each stage; correctness grows with encounter.</p>',

    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: the authorities\' disbelief that the man had been blind signals the depth of their resistance — they will not accept the sign\'s premise. They move from adjudicating the miracle to denying its preconditions. The Evangelist shows that unbelief does not simply lack evidence; it progressively reconstructs the evidence to avoid the conclusion. This is the blindness Christ names in vv39–41: not the blindness of those who cannot see, but the blindness of those who refuse to.</p>',

    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: the parents are summoned because family testimony is the most credible in Jewish legal procedure (Deut 19:15 — two witnesses). The authorities assume the parents will provide a rationalizing account. Instead, the parents confirm both facts — son, born blind — and deflect on the how. The Evangelist uses the parental testimony to fence off every denial: the only fact in question is now the healing itself and its source.</p>',

    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: the parents\' testimony is bare but decisive — "We know he is our son and we know he was born blind." Two facts that close off two escape routes for the Pharisees. The irony is that the most unimpeachable witnesses in the narrative confirm the sign\'s premise even as they refuse to testify about its agent. Truth emerges even through those who are trying to limit it.</p>',

    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: the parents\' deflection — "ask him, he is of age" — functions in the narrative as a handing-off that places the healed man alone before his interrogators. The Evangelist structures the scene so that the one who received the sign must now testify to it without support. The isolation is the preparation for the confession that follows: the man who will be cast out will meet Christ on the other side. Abandonment by family becomes the occasion for encounter with the Shepherd.</p>',

    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "anyone who acknowledged that Jesus was the Messiah would be put out of the synagogue" — this is the Evangelist\'s explicit narrative of what it costs to confess Christ. The synagogue was the center of Jewish social, religious, and economic life; expulsion meant genuine social death. The cost-of-confession theme runs through the Gospel (12:42–43; 19:38) and connects to Christ\'s own casting-out in 19:16–18. Discipleship in the Fourth Gospel is marked by the willingness to go outside the gate with the one who was cast outside it.</p>',

    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: the parents\' repeated deflection — "he is of age, ask him" — closes the parental testimony unit and leaves the man alone. The Evangelist shows no blame for the parents\' caution; their testimony was true and their silence understandable. But the trajectory of the narrative now runs through the son alone: to be the witness to Christ in a hostile environment, he must face the cost himself. The communal shelter that Torah promised has become a threat; the man will find his shelter elsewhere.</p>',

    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "Give glory to God by telling the truth — we know this man is a sinner" is the formula for swearing to tell the truth under oath (cf. Josh 7:19). The Pharisees demand that the man ratify their verdict as the truth. The irony is compressed: they call for truth-telling in order to get the man to confirm a falsehood. "Give glory to God" is exactly what the sign was designed for (v3 — "so that the works of God might be displayed"). The man will give that glory — by refusing to deny what God actually did.</p>',

    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "whether he is a sinner or not, I don\'t know — one thing I do know: I was blind but now I see" is the epistemological starting point of all authentic Christian witness. The man does not claim to have resolved the theological dispute; he reports what happened to him. The Evangelist presents this as the most defensible form of testimony: not argument but evidence. The statement will echo across church history as the model of the convert\'s witness — the argument from transformation.</p>',

    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: the Pharisees\' repeated question — "what did he do?" — reveals that the sign itself is what they cannot absorb into their framework. They must hear it again, hoping for a version that will permit a different verdict. The Evangelist shows that the sign\'s effect on the resistant hearer is not enlightenment but frustration. The same event that opened one man\'s eyes increasingly deepens the others\' blindness.</p>',

    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: the healed man\'s sharpening boldness — "do you want to become his disciples too?" — is the Evangelist\'s ironic turning of the tables. The interrogated has become the interrogator. Under threat of synagogue expulsion, the man advances in confidence rather than retreating in fear. The Christological pattern: those who genuinely encounter Christ are not made more timid by opposition but bolder, because what they have received cannot be taken from them.</p>',

    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: the Pharisees\' "we are disciples of Moses" is a confession of allegiance that reveals the core conflict. They are not claiming that what Jesus did is impossible — they have just accepted that it happened — but that his authority is unauthorized by the frame of reference they trust. The Evangelist has built this contrast from 1:17: the law through Moses, grace and truth through Jesus Christ. The two are not enemies, but they are not equivalent. Moses pointed to the one before whom the Pharisees now choose Moses.</p>',

    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "we don\'t know where he comes from" — the Pharisees\' ignorance of Christ\'s origin is the irony the Evangelist has been building from 7:27–28. They think they know where the Messiah should come from (not Galilee, not Nazareth). They do not know where Christ actually comes from: from the Father, from above, from eternity. The man born blind will prove to know more than they do, not from training but from encounter.</p>',

    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: the healed man\'s counter — "now that is remarkable! You don\'t know where he comes from, yet he opened my eyes" — is the Gospel\'s argument from effect. The sign is the evidence that answers the question of origin. The one whose origin is unknown performed what is unprecedented (v32); the unprecedented act attests a divine origin that no official category can account for. The man reasons from evidence; the Pharisees reason from precedent. The Evangelist shows which reasoning leads to truth.</p>',

    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "God does not listen to sinners; he listens to the godly person who does his will" — the healed man applies the standard biblical theology of answered prayer (Ps 66:18; Isa 1:15; Prov 15:29). He does not yet know the full truth about Christ; he is reasoning from what he knows about God. His conclusion is correct: the one whose prayer God answered is not a sinner operating outside divine authorization. The sign answers the charge before it is formally made.</p>',

    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "nobody has ever heard of opening the eyes of a man born blind" is a claim about the uniqueness of the sign. Elijah and Elisha raised the dead (1 Kgs 17; 2 Kgs 4); prophets performed signs of healing. But congenital blindness had no precedent of cure. The man is not simply arguing from analogy but from the sign\'s own singularity: this is beyond what God has done through any previous agent. The threshold of the claim is therefore higher than any previous prophetic authorization could establish.</p>',

    "33": '<p>A direct testimony from the healed man: "if this man were not from God, he could do nothing" arrives at the same conclusion the authorities reached in 3:2 ("no one could perform the signs you are doing if God were not with him") — from within the frame of the interrogation designed to reach the opposite conclusion. The one who was blind has seen more clearly than the sighted investigators. The Evangelist has structured the chapter so that the testimony of the healed man outweighs the judgment of the authorities.</p>',

    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "you were steeped in sin at birth — how dare you lecture us!" — the Pharisees return to the retribution theology of v2 (birth-sin) to dismiss the man. The irony is total: they are refuting the man using the very theological framework Christ dismantled in v3. Their conclusion ("steeped in sin at birth") is precisely the diagnosis Christ refused. And by expelling the man, they enact the social equivalent of what they accuse Christ of — they cast out the one whose testimony is inconvenient. Their throwing-out is the occasion for Christ\'s seeking.</p>',

    "35": '<p>A direct revelation: Christ hears that the man was cast out and seeks him. The Shepherd-language of ch. 10 is already operative: the one who will say "I lay down my life for the sheep" (10:11) finds the sheep that the fold has expelled. The question "Do you believe in the Son of Man?" — using the Daniel 7:13-14 title — is the first moment the man is invited into explicit Christological confession. He was healed without knowing who Jesus was; now the question of who Jesus is becomes the question of his life.</p>',

    "36": '<p>A direct revelation: "who is he, sir, so that I may believe in him?" — the man\'s posture is the Gospel\'s model of faith-readiness. He is not skeptical or resistant; he asks the question that requires an honest answer. The Evangelist places this at the pivot of the chapter: the healed man, expelled by the religious community, is ready to believe in the Son of Man as soon as he knows who that is. The only thing standing between him and faith is information, and Christ is about to supply it.</p>',

    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "you have now seen him; in fact, he is the one speaking with you" — this is Christ\'s most direct self-disclosure to an individual in the Gospel up to this point (surpassing even 4:26 in that it uses seeing as the medium: the man whose eyes Christ opened now sees, literally, the Son of Man). The physical restoration and the spiritual revelation are held together: the one who gave him eyes to see stands before eyes that can now see him. The sign and the disclosure are one event in two moments.</p>',

    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "Lord, I believe" — followed by worship (<em>prosekunēsen</em>, the verb used for the worship of God). The healed man offers what the Evangelist has been building toward across the chapter: explicit faith and the act of worship directed at Christ. He is the first figure in the Gospel to respond to a direct self-disclosure of Christ with worship. The scene enacts the promise of 1:12 — those who receive him and believe in his name are given authority to become children of God. The cast-out man becomes the confessing worshiper.</p>',

    "39": '<p>A fulfillment: "for judgment I have come into this world, so that the blind will see and those who see will become blind" fulfills the reversal-of-blindness promise of Isaiah 29:18 ("in that day the deaf will hear the words of the scroll, and out of gloom and darkness the eyes of the blind will see") and the judgment-through-encounter of Isaiah 6:9–10 (the word of God simultaneously opens and hardens). Christ\'s presence is eschatological judgment made present: encounter with the light determines whether one sees or is blinded. The judgment of ch. 9 has just been enacted.</p>',

    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: the Pharisees\' indignant question — "are we blind too?" — is the moment of ironic self-exposure. They have watched the entire chapter unfold, conducted two interrogations, expelled a credible witness, and heard the healed man\'s escalating theological clarity. Their question is half-defensive, half-genuine: they are beginning to feel the accusation of blindness that the narrative has been building. But they frame it as indignation rather than inquiry — which is why Christ\'s answer takes the form it does in v41.</p>',

    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: "if you were blind, you would not be guilty of sin; but now that you claim you can see, your guilt remains" — the Christological verdict of chapter 9. The blindness that incurs guilt is not the blindness of ignorance but the blindness of refused sight. The Pharisees have seen the sign, heard the testimony, and insisted on a conclusion that denies it. This is the sin the Prologue named ("the darkness did not overcome it") — not ignorance of the light but rejection of it in full view. The chapter closes with the man seeing and worshiping; the authorities seeing and guilty. The light divides as it illuminates.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: the chapter opens with the Evangelist\'s address — "Truly, truly, I tell you Pharisees" — making the parable of the sheepfold a direct word to the men who just expelled the healed man. The thief who enters by another way is a figure the Pharisees themselves instantiate: they have positioned themselves as the gatekeepers of Israel\'s covenant but have used their authority to exclude the one whom Christ healed and sought. The authorized-entry language sets the framework in which Christ will identify himself as both the gate and the shepherd — the two figures the false guardians have counterfeited.</p>',

    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "the one who enters by the gate is the shepherd of the sheep" — the contrast between legitimate access (gate) and illegitimate access (climbing over) defines the entire discourse. The shepherd of Israel in the OT entered the covenant life of the people through the appointed means of divine election and commissioning (Moses, David, the prophets). Christ\'s entrance is through the gate because he is himself the gate (v7) — the authorized way and the authorizing source are the same person.</p>',

    "3": '<p>A direct type fulfilling the Shepherd-typology of Ezekiel 34: "he calls his own sheep by name and leads them out." In Ezekiel 34:11–16, God himself promises to search for, find, and lead his scattered flock — because the human shepherds of Israel have failed. The name-calling is significant: to know by name is the intimacy of the covenant relationship (Exod 33:12, "I know you by name"). Christ knows each sheep individually, a knowledge the false shepherds could not offer.</p>',

    "4": '<p>A direct type: "the sheep follow him because they know his voice" — the recognition of the shepherd\'s voice is the OT idiom for covenant loyalty and divine guidance. Isaiah 30:21 promises "your ears will hear a voice behind you saying, \'this is the way\'"; the Servant of Isaiah 50:4–5 has "an instructed tongue" to sustain the weary and opens his ear to hear. The sheep of Christ follow because they have been given ears to hear — a gift of divine election, not natural capacity.</p>',

    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "they will never follow a stranger; in fact, they will run away from him" — the negative counterpart of v4 establishes the security of the sheep\'s discernment. Those who belong to Christ cannot ultimately be deceived into following a false shepherd, because the voice is unrecognizable to them. The theme of election and perseverance (vv28–29) is anticipated here: the sheep who flee the stranger\'s voice are the same sheep from whose hands no one will snatch them.</p>',

    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus used this figure of speech, but the Pharisees did not understand" — the Evangelist marks the parable\'s opacity for its audience before Christ interprets it. The pattern is structural: those who think they can see (v41) are the ones who cannot hear what is being said to them. The figure of speech (<em>paroimia</em> — a dark saying or proverb) requires interpretation because the hearers\' framework cannot receive its meaning. Christ will interpret it in vv7–18 for those willing to hear.</p>',

    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: the first "I am the gate" (<em>egō eimi hē thyra</em>) — one of the Johannine I AM declarations with a predicate noun. The gate is not merely a metaphor for access; in the sheepfold it is the controlled point through which life, safety, and belonging pass. Christ\'s identification of himself as the gate claims that all legitimate entry into God\'s people, all legitimate access to the Father, all legitimate share in the covenant flock, passes through him. There is no side entrance.</p>',

    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "all who have come before me are thieves and robbers" — interpreted as referring to those who falsely claimed to lead Israel (false shepherds of Ezek 34, false messiahs of the Second Temple period). The charge is not that Moses or the prophets were thieves but that those who used their offices to exploit rather than serve the flock — including the authorities who just expelled the healed man — are numbered among those who entered by another way. The sheep, crucially, "have not listened to them" — the elect discern the false voice.</p>',

    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "I am the gate; whoever enters through me will be saved" — the gate imagery reaches its Christological apex. "Saved" (<em>sōthēsetai</em>) is the salvation vocabulary used sparingly but pointedly by the Evangelist (3:17; 5:34; 12:47). The freedom of movement ("will come in and go out and find pasture") echoes Psalm 118:20 ("this is the gate of the Lord through which the righteous may enter") and Numbers 27:17 (the leader who will let the people "go out and come in"). Christ is the gate through which Israel sought entry; he is also the pasture they sought inside it.</p>',

    "10": '<p>A direct contrast: the thief\'s agenda (steal, kill, destroy) versus Christ\'s mission (life, and life to the full). The contrast is between false leadership — which extracts from the flock for its own benefit — and the true shepherd\'s abundant generosity. "Life to the full" (<em>perisson</em> — exceedingly, beyond measure) connects to the abundance of the Cana wine (2:7, filled to the brim) and the Prologue\'s "fullness from which we have all received" (1:16). The mission of the Son is not minimum survival but overflowing life — the eschatological abundance Isaiah 25:6 and 55:1–2 describe.</p>',

    "11": '<p>A direct type fulfilling multiple OT strands: "I am the good shepherd; the good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep." The OT background is rich and explicit. Ezekiel 34 depicts God himself as the shepherd who will replace the false shepherds of Israel — who fed themselves rather than the flock. Psalm 23 describes the Lord as the shepherd who provides, restores, and accompanies through the valley of death. Isaiah 40:11 pictures God feeding his flock and carrying the lambs. In each strand God is the true shepherd. The Evangelist presents Christ as the fulfillment of what those texts promised: God himself has come as the shepherd, and the good shepherd\'s definitive act is to die for the sheep.</p>',

    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: the hired hand who "does not own the sheep" and flees when danger comes represents every form of leadership — political, religious, or pastoral — that is accountable to a salary rather than to a relationship of ownership and love. The Evangelist is not merely critiquing specific leaders; he is establishing that no human leader can be the true shepherd, because no human leader owns the flock or is bound to it by the bond that Christ names in v14-15 (mutual knowledge as between Father and Son). Only the one who truly owns — and truly loves — will lay down his life.</p>',

    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "he cares nothing for the sheep" — the motive of the hired hand is self-preservation, not love. The contrast with Christ\'s voluntary death (vv17–18) is stark. Every false shepherd, in biblical idiom from Jeremiah (23:1–4) to Zechariah (11:4–17), used the flock for his own gain. Christ\'s death proves he is not a hired hand: no one who cares only for himself dies for those who cannot protect him.</p>',

    "14": '<p>A direct type: "I am the good shepherd; I know my sheep and my sheep know me" — the mutual knowledge is modeled on the Father-Son relationship in v15. To be known by God is the covenant blessing (Exod 33:12; Amos 3:2; Jer 1:5); to know God is the goal of the new covenant (Jer 31:34 — "they will all know me"). Christ is the one through whom both sides of the covenant knowledge-relationship are fulfilled: he knows his sheep with the Father\'s own knowing; they know him in the knowledge the new covenant promised.</p>',

    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "just as the Father knows me and I know the Father" — the sheep\'s knowledge of Christ is grounded in the same mutual knowing that defines the Father-Son relationship. The logic is participatory: because Christ knows the Father perfectly, and the sheep know Christ, the sheep are drawn into the relational orbit of the Trinity. The atonement is not a mechanical transaction but an extension of the divine life into the creaturely: "and I lay down my life for the sheep" is the way the divine life enters the sheep\'s life.</p>',

    "16": '<p>A fulfillment: "other sheep that are not of this sheep pen" — the Gentile mission anticipated before it begins. The "one flock and one shepherd" fulfills Ezekiel 37:22–24 (the two kingdoms of Israel reunited under one king, one shepherd) and Micah 5:4 (the ruler from Bethlehem who will shepherd in the strength of the Lord, whose greatness will reach to the ends of the earth). The Evangelist has already shown Christ\'s outreach beyond Israel — to Samaritans (ch. 4), to a Gentile official (4:46) — and here Christ names the design: the flock is wider than Israel, and the one shepherd will gather it all.</p>',

    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "the reason my Father loves me is that I lay down my life — only to take it up again" — the death and resurrection are stated as a single voluntary act motivated by the Father\'s love. The death is not something imposed on a reluctant Son; it is the act through which the Father\'s love for the Son is expressed and the Son\'s love for the Father is enacted. The pattern is not sacrifice-despite-love but sacrifice-as-love-made-visible. The resurrection ("only to take it up again") is the Father\'s ratification of the Son\'s sacrifice — not merely an appendix to the death but its necessary completion.</p>',

    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "no one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord. I have authority to lay it down and authority to take it up again" — the divine authority over death is stated with maximum explicitness. No human agent, no Roman soldier, no conspiracy of priests takes Christ\'s life; he gives it. The authority to lay down and take up his own life is the authority of the one who is the source of life (1:4) and who will speak the resurrection of the dead (5:28–29; 11:43). The cross is not victimhood but sovereign act.</p>',

    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: the division among the Jews in response to the Good Shepherd discourse mirrors the division in 9:16. The Evangelist shows that Christ\'s words — like his signs — are themselves the crisis: they divide those who hear into those who respond with accusation and those who see the signs\'s import. The shepherd discourse, addressed to the Pharisees, has not silenced opposition; it has deepened the fault line that runs through ch. 9.</p>',

    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "he is demon-possessed and raving mad — why listen to him?" is the formal accusation that attributes the works of God to demonic power. The logic is perverse: the one who gave a blind man sight, who calls the dead by name (ch. 11), who speaks with divine authority is dismissed as demonized. The accusation was made in 7:20 and 8:48; it will recur. The Evangelist presents it as the terminal form of unbelief — the refusal not of evidence but of the source of evidence.</p>',

    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: the counter from others — "these are not the sayings of a man possessed by a demon; can a demon open the eyes of the blind?" — is the argument from the sign that the healed man himself made (9:30–33). The sign is the evidence that refuses the accusation. The Evangelist places this counter in the mouth of unnamed voices who reason honestly from what they have seen, in contrast to the authorities who reason from predetermined conclusions. The sign of ch. 9 continues to divide in ch. 10.</p>',

    "22": '<p>A shadow: the Festival of Dedication (<em>Hanukkah</em>) commemorated the rededication of the Second Temple after Antiochus IV Epiphanes desecrated it (167–164 BCE). The festival celebrated the faithfulness of God to his sanctuary and the light of the Menorah that miraculously burned for eight days. Christ is present at the feast of the temple\'s restoration — the Evangelist\'s irony is that the one who is the true temple (2:21) and the true light (1:5; 8:12; 9:5) is present at the feast that celebrates the restoration of shadow institutions. The season anticipates the question of v24: are you the Messiah?</p>',

    "23": '<p>A shadow: Solomon\'s Colonnade was the eastern portico of the temple complex, associated with the earliest temple structure (1 Kgs 6) and with the later post-exilic hope of restoration (Ezek 40–48). Christ walks where Solomon\'s name is attached — but he is the one of whom Solomon\'s temple was a shadow (2:21; cf. Matt 12:42, "one greater than Solomon is here"). The geography of the scene places him in the space where the fullness of what the temple only represented is present in person.</p>',

    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: the demand — "if you are the Messiah, tell us plainly" — is the question the authorities have been circling since ch. 5. Christ has already told them: through the signs, through the I AM declarations, through the Good Shepherd discourse just delivered. Their demand for plain speech reflects not a genuine openness but a desire for a statement clear enough to be used as a charge. The Evangelist has repeatedly shown that those who demand a sign or a statement as the precondition for belief will not believe the sign or statement when given (2:18–20; 8:25–27).</p>',

    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "I did tell you, but you do not believe. The works I do in my Father\'s name testify about me" — Christ has testified both in word (8:12, 58; 9:37; 10:7, 11, 14) and in deed (five signs so far in the Gospel). The failure to believe is not a failure of evidence but a failure of the will to receive it. The language "in my Father\'s name" frames every work as a commissioned act of the Son — not independent demonstration but filial obedience that the Father endorses.</p>',

    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "but you do not believe because you are not my sheep" — the logic of election is stated with unusual directness. Belief is not the precondition for belonging to the flock; belonging to the flock is the condition that enables genuine belief. The Pharisees demand a declaration that will produce faith, but the Evangelist shows that the issue runs deeper: the sheep hear the voice because they are sheep, not vice versa. This is not fatalism — the entire Gospel calls for belief — but it names the theological reality that faith is the fruit of a prior divine gift.</p>',

    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "my sheep listen to my voice; I know them, and they follow me" — the three-part characterization of the sheep (they hear, they are known, they follow) is the Johannine description of the Christian life in miniature. Hearing/believing (1:12; 5:24), being known by God (10:14), and following (1:37–43; 8:12; 21:19–22) are the recurring verbs of Johannine discipleship. The sheep are not defined by their performance but by their relationship to the Shepherd.</p>',

    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "I give them eternal life, and they shall never perish; no one will snatch them out of my hand" — the security of the sheep is grounded in Christ\'s giving, not their holding. "Eternal life" is the Evangelist\'s term for the life of the age to come given now (3:16; 5:24; 6:47). The "hand" of Christ is the hand of the one who holds the sheep by virtue of divine authority — the same hand that will be pierced at the cross (20:27). The one who gives life through death holds the sheep securely in the hands that death could not hold.</p>',

    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "my Father, who has given them to me, is greater than all; no one can snatch them out of my Father\'s hand" — the double security (Christ\'s hand, the Father\'s hand) grounds the sheep\'s safety in the full Trinitarian reality. The sheep given by the Father to the Son are held simultaneously by both — not because Father and Son are undifferentiated, but because they are one in the way that v30 will immediately announce. The Evangelist moves from pastoral assurance directly into the highest Christological claim of the chapter.</p>',

    "30": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "I and the Father are one" (<em>egō kai ho patēr hen esmen</em>). The neuter <em>hen</em> (one thing, not one person) affirms unity of essence and purpose without collapsing the distinction of persons — a distinction the Gospel has maintained throughout (1:1–2, "with God" and "was God"). The authorities immediately understand this as a claim to be God (v33 — "you, a mere man, claim to be God") and respond with stoning. The Evangelist presents their interpretation as correct in what it grasps, though they act wrongly in response. The claim is the apex of the discourse: the Good Shepherd who lays down his life is one with the Father who holds the sheep.</p>',

    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: the attempt to stone Christ for the declaration of v30 is the ironic culmination of the Hanukkah setting. At the festival celebrating the temple\'s deliverance from those who would desecrate it, the one who is the true temple is threatened with death by the guardians of the restored institution. The pattern of the rejected stone (Ps 118:22) is operative: the cornerstone the builders reject is the one YHWH has chosen. The stoning attempt is also the third such attempt in the Gospel (5:18; 8:59) — the opposition escalates toward the authorized death of 19:16.</p>',

    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have shown you many good works from the Father — for which of these do you stone me?" — Christ\'s challenge inverts the legal burden. The sign-works are the Father\'s testimony (5:36); to stone the sign-worker is to stone the Father\'s witness. The question forces the authorities to articulate what they are actually objecting to — which they do in v33, naming the theological issue accurately: not the works, but the claim of divine identity.</p>',

    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "you, a mere man, claim to be God" — the charge that will appear on no formal warrant at the trial (18:29–19:7) but has been the real accusation since 5:18. The authorities have heard Christ correctly: the claim of v30 is a claim to divine identity. Their response is stoning under the law (Lev 24:16 — blasphemy is punishable by stoning). The Evangelist does not present their hearing as a misinterpretation; it is an accurate hearing followed by a wrong verdict. They stone not because they misunderstood but because they did understand and rejected it.</p>',

    "34": '<p>A direct argument: the quotation from Psalm 82:6 — "I have said you are gods" — is a fortiori reasoning. If the Scripture calls the human judges of Israel "gods" (without any claim to divine essence — simply because God\'s word came to them and they bore his authority), then the term "God\'s Son" is not blasphemous when applied to the one whom the Father uniquely set apart and sent. Christ does not use this as the full explanation of his divine nature; he uses it as a defense against the blasphemy charge by showing that the language of divinity has wider scriptural application than the Pharisees\'s literalism acknowledges.</p>',

    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "scripture cannot be set aside" — Christ grounds his argument in the inviolability of the text his accusers also revere. The authority of scripture is presented not as an appeal to their sentiment but as an axiom they share: if the text cannot be annulled, and the text says "gods" of human judges, then the charge of blasphemy against a term the text itself applies (in a lesser register) cannot stand. The argument is formal and precise — the Evangelist presents Christ as a rigorous exegete of the tradition that is being used against him.</p>',

    "36": '<p>A direct revelation: "what about the one whom the Father set apart as his very own and sent into the world?" — the term "set apart" (<em>hēgiasen</em>) is the language of consecration and holiness, applied to Christ as the one uniquely dedicated by the Father for the mission of redemption. The Evangelist presents consecration and sending as the two defining acts of the Father toward the Son: he is consecrated (set apart as holy for the Father\'s purpose) and sent (dispatched into the world as the agent of salvation). Blasphemy cannot attach to the one whom God himself has consecrated and commissioned.</p>',

    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: "do not believe me unless I do the works of my Father" — Christ\'s appeal to the works is not an abandonment of the word-claim; it is a gracious concession to those who cannot yet receive the word alone. The works are the Father\'s testimony (5:36), and they point to the Father-Son relationship even for those unwilling to accept the declaration directly. The patience of this appeal — even after the stoning attempt — reflects the divine long-suffering that the Evangelist has shown throughout: Christ continues to give evidence to those who have already rejected him.</p>',

    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "that you may know and understand that the Father is in me, and I in the Father" — the mutual indwelling (perichoresis, as later theology will name it) is the theological statement that the works attest. To understand the works is to understand that the Father and Son are not merely in agreement but interpenetrating — the Father\'s life is in the Son\'s life and the Son\'s life is in the Father\'s. This mutual indwelling will be the theme of the Farewell Discourse (14:10–11, 20; 17:21–23), applied to the disciples who will participate in this same unity.</p>',

    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: the attempt to seize him fails — "he escaped their grasp." The departure from Jerusalem is not flight but timing: the hour has not yet come (7:30; 8:20; 12:23). Christ operates within a divine schedule that no human opposition can accelerate. The Evangelist has shown this repeatedly: no arrest attempt succeeds until the authorized hour (18:4–8, where Christ himself delivers himself). His security is not circumstantial but sovereign.</p>',

    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: Christ returns to Bethany beyond the Jordan — the place of John the Baptist\'s ministry (1:28) and of the original witness to his identity. The retreat to the source is both geographical and theological: where the testimony began, Christ returns. The Evangelist marks the movement as purposeful, not desperate. The one who declared himself the light of the world, the gate, and the Good Shepherd withdraws from the city that wants to stone him — not in defeat, but on the way to the hour.</p>',

    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: the crowds at Bethany say "though John never performed a sign, all that John said about this man was true." The Baptist\'s prophetic witness is vindicated retroactively: the one John said would baptize with the Spirit (1:33), would take away the world\'s sin (1:29), who was before him though coming after him (1:30) — all of it has been demonstrated in the chapters since 1:19. John the Baptist is the last of the OT prophets whose words preceded the event; now the event has come, and those who stand at the place of his witness recognize the correspondence.</p>',

    "42": '<p>A theme: "in that place many believed in Jesus" — the same faith-through-testimony pattern as 4:39–42, where the Samaritans believed first through the woman\'s word and then through encounter. Here faith is through the Baptist\'s accumulated witness rather than direct encounter with a sign. The Evangelist bookends the chapters of mounting opposition in Jerusalem (5–10) with this note of belief at the margins — outside the city, outside the institutional center, where John prepared the way, many receive what Jerusalem has refused. The Gospel is spreading through exactly the channels of witness the Prologue described.</p>'
  }
}


